1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:04,473
Most agent tasks do not fail because the model needs a more clever prompt.

2
00:00:04,423 --> 00:00:14,115
They fail because the assignment begins with a blank box while the real work is scattered across documents, messages, spreadsheets, decisions, and unspoken expectations.

3
00:00:14,115 --> 00:00:23,682
OpenAI's guidance for everyday work starts from a different premise: give the agent the materials your team already uses and ask for the first usable version of a concrete artifact.

4
00:00:23,682 --> 00:00:26,451
The goal is not a beautiful conversation.

5
00:00:26,451 --> 00:00:30,480
The goal is work that someone can inspect, edit, and continue.

6
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:33,355
That changes what a good handoff contains.

7
00:00:33,355 --> 00:00:39,490
The agent needs source materials, constraints, review expectations, and a destination format.

8
00:00:39,490 --> 00:00:43,201
It also needs a clear definition of the artifact you want back.

9
00:00:43,201 --> 00:00:47,509
In this video, we will turn those elements into an Agent Task Brief.

10
00:00:47,509 --> 00:00:57,076
You will learn how to choose the artifact, package the right context, define boundaries, make review observable, and specify a delivery format that survives the handoff.

11
00:00:57,076 --> 00:01:01,980
Keep one principle in view: do not ask an agent to understand your entire world.

12
00:01:01,980 --> 00:01:06,480
Give it the smallest complete package required to produce a review-ready first version.
